  "prompt": "What is the difference between overhanging beam and cantilever beam?",
  "response": "While both overhanging beams and cantilever beams have sections extending beyond their supports, the key difference lies in their **support conditions** and the resulting **behavior under load.**\n\nHere's a breakdown:\n\n**Cantilever Beam:**\n\n*   **Support:** Fixed (or encastr\u00e9) at one end only.  The fixed end provides both vertical and rotational restraint.\n*   **Overhang:** The entire beam extends from the fixed support.\n*   **Behavior:**  Deflects downwards away from the fixed end under load.  Experiences maximum bending moment and shear force at the fixed support. The upper fibers of the beam are in tension, and the lower fibers are in compression.\n*   **Examples:** Balconies, diving boards, airplane wings.\n\n**Overhanging Beam:**\n\n*   **Support:** Supported at two or more points, with a portion of the beam extending beyond one or both of the supports.\n*   **Overhang:** A segment of the beam extends *past* a support.\n*   **Behavior:** The overhang can cause the beam to deflect upwards in certain regions depending on the location and magnitude of the load. The moment distribution is more complex than a cantilever. It may experience both positive (sagging) and negative (hogging) bending moments.\n*   **Examples:** Bridges, floor beams extending beyond supporting columns.\n\n**Here's a table summarizing the key differences:**\n\n| Feature        | Cantilever Beam                      | Overhanging Beam                            |\n|----------------|---------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------|\n| **Support**      | Fixed at one end                   | Two or more supports, with an overhang      |\n| **Overhang**     | Entire length is an overhang       | Only a portion extends beyond a support     |\n| **Moment at Support** | Maximum at the fixed support          | Varies depending on loads and support positions |\n| **Deflection**   | Typically downward (away from fixed end)| More complex; can deflect up or down          |\n| **Number of Supports** |One | Two or More |\n\n**In essence:**\n\n*   A **cantilever** is only fixed at *one* point, and the entire beam extends from that fixed point.\n*   An **overhanging beam** is supported at *multiple* points, and a portion of the beam extends past one or more of these supports.  The overhangs change the bending moment distribution compared to a simple supported beam.\n\nThinking about it in terms of real-world examples can help:  A balcony attached only at the wall is a cantilever. A bridge deck supported by piers with the deck extending slightly beyond the piers is an overhanging beam.\n",
